  "response": "# Verdict: REJECT\n\n## Overall Assessment\n\nThis file input component has **critical accessibility failures** that block screen reader users from understanding what field they're interacting with and how errors relate to it. The visual label \"Upload file\" is not accessible, error messages are unassociated, and no programmatic state communicates validation status. This violates fundamental WCAG 1.3.1 (Info and Relationships) requirements.\n\n## Pre-commitment Predictions\n\nBefore reading code:\n- **Predicted**: Missing `<label>` association with input \u2014 HIGH CONFIDENCE for file inputs without explicit label elements\n- **Predicted**: Error messages not associated via `aria-describedby` \u2014 HIGH CONFIDENCE based on comment in code\n- **Predicted**: No `aria-invalid` state when error present \u2014 HIGH CONFIDENCE (code shows no implementation)\n- **Predicted**: Help text about file types not accessible to AT \u2014 MEDIUM CONFIDENCE\n\n**Actual findings match predictions exactly.** The component has all predicted issues.\n\n---\n\n## Critical Findings\n\n### 1. File Input Has No Accessible Label\n\n```jsx\n<div>Upload file</div>\n<input type=\"file\" onChange={handleFileChange} accept=\".pdf,.doc,.docx\" />\n// src/components/FileInput.tsx:23-26 (line numbers approximate)\n```\n\n**Evidence**: The visual text \"Upload file\" is in a `<div>` element, not associated with the input. No `for` attribute on label, no nested structure, and no programmatic association via `aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`, or wrapping pattern.\n\n- **User group impacted**: Screen reader users (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)\n- **WCAG/APG citation**: WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships; WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide File Upload Pattern\n- **Why this matters**: Screen readers announce \"input file\" with no name or description. Users cannot understand what data field they're filling out, violating the fundamental principle that all form controls must be labeled.\n\n**Fix Required**: Wrap input in `<label>` element OR use `aria-label=\"Upload file\"` on input OR nest text inside label:\n```jsx\n<label htmlFor=\"file-input\" className=\"file-upload\">\n  Upload file\n  <input \n    id=\"file-input\"\n    type=\"file\"\n    onChange={handleFileChange}\n    accept=\".pdf,.doc,.docx\"\n    aria-describedby=\"error-message-file-help-text\"\n    aria-invalid={!!error}\n  />\n</label>\n\n<div id=\"error-message-file-help-text\">{error}</div>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. Error Messages Not Associated with Input Field\n\n```jsx\n{error && (\n  <div className=\"error-message\">\n    {error}\n  </div>\n)}\n// src/components/FileInput.tsx:30-34\n```\n\n**Evidence**: The error div has no `id` attribute and the input has no `aria-describedby`. Screen reader users will hear \"File too large\" announced but won't know which field it relates to. They may not understand this is a validation error for THIS specific control.\n\n- **User group impacted**: Screen reader users, keyboard-only users (who rely on aria-live regions)\n- **WCAG/APG citation**: WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships; WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide Form Validation Pattern\n- **Why this matters**: Without association, screen readers announce the error but don't connect it to the field needing correction. Users may not know which file input failed validation, leading to confusion and repeated errors.\n\n**Fix Required**: Add `id` to error element and link via `aria-describedby`:\n```jsx\n<div id=\"file-error-message\" className=\"error-message\">\n  {error}\n</div>\n\n<input \n  type=\"file\"\n  aria-describedby={error ? \"file-error-message file-help-text\" : undefined}\n/>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. No `aria-invalid` State When Error Present\n\n**Evidence**: The code sets error state but never updates the input's ARIA attributes:\n- Input has no `aria-invalid=\"true\"` when validation fails\n- Code comment explicitly notes this is a bug (line ~25)\n\n- **User group impacted**: Screen reader users, keyboard-only users relying on AT for field status\n- **WCAG/APG citation**: WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages; WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide Form Validation Pattern\n- **Why this matters**: Assistive technology needs to know the field is in an invalid state so it can announce appropriately and guide users to corrections. Without `aria-invalid`, AT treats the input as valid even when errors exist, creating a disconnect between visual feedback (red border) and programmatic state.\n\n**Fix Required**: Conditionally set `aria-invalid` attribute:\n```jsx\n<input \n  type=\"file\"\n  aria-invalid={error ? \"true\" : undefined}\n/>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. Help Text About File Types Not Accessible to AT\n\n**Evidence**: The code specifies `accept=\".pdf,.doc,.docx\"` but provides no accessible help text explaining file restrictions:\n- No `<span>` or paragraph with instructions about allowed formats\n- No association via `aria-describedby` even if such text existed elsewhere in the component tree\n\n- **User group impacted**: Screen reader users, cognitive accessibility users who need clear guidance\n- **WCAG/APG citation**: WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships; WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide Form Help Text Pattern\n- **Why this matters**: Users with AT won't know they can only upload PDF/DOC files unless help text is explicitly provided and associated. This creates an information gap that may cause users to attempt unsupported file types unnecessarily.\n\n**Fix Required**: Add accessible help text:\n```jsx\n<div id=\"file-help-text\">\n  Acceptable formats: .pdf, .doc, .docx (max 5MB)\n</div>\n<input \n  aria-describedby={error ? \"file-error-message\" : undefined}\n/>\n\n{!error && <span className=\"help\">{/* help text */}</span>}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Major Findings\n\n### 1. No Focus Management Design for Error State Transition\n\n**Evidence**: When error is set, the component doesn't manage focus:\n- Input remains focused but user may not realize they need to correct it\n- No automatic refocus after validation fails (common pattern)\n- Escape key handling undefined if modal context existed elsewhere in app\n\n- **User group impacted**: Keyboard-only users, screen reader users relying on AT for navigation flow\n- **WCAG/APG citation**: WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard; WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide Form Validation Pattern\n- **Why this matters**: After validation fails, focus should ideally move to the error message or remain on input so user knows where they need to act next. Current design leaves keyboard users stranded at an invalid field without clear guidance.\n\n**Fix Suggestion**: Consider refocusing after async operations:\n```jsx\nuseEffect(() => {\n  if (error) {\n    // Optionally move focus to error or keep on input for correction\n    const el = document.getElementById('file-input');\n    setTimeout(() => el?.focus(), 10);\n  }\n}, [error]);\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. Missing `aria-describedby` When Error Is Present (Partial Implementation)\n\n**Evidence**: The error div exists but has no ID, and input never references it:\n- Code comment at line ~34 notes this is a bug\n- No implementation of the association pattern even when error state changes\n\n- **User group impacted**: Screen reader users who need to know which field failed validation\n- **WCAG/APG citation**: WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships; WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide Form Validation Pattern  \n- **Why this matters**: This is a partial implementation \u2014 the error exists visually but AT cannot connect it to the control. The pattern requires BOTH an ID on the message AND reference in input's `aria-describedby`.\n\n---\n\n## Minor Findings\n\n### 1. No Language Attribute Declaration\n\n**Evidence**: File doesn't show `<html lang=\"en\">` or component-level language context (though this is typically at page level,",
